re ageing, and we need to identify sustainable and person-centred solutions for supporting frail older people in their homes. Reablement offers a radical new integrated care approach which supports older people to regain and maintain functioning and independence. This interdisciplinary book provides an introduction to the remarkable, if haphazard, international growth in reablement policies and practices in aged care over the past 20 years. Incorporating theoretical and empirical research, it considers benefits for clients and care workers, cost-saving potentials and reablement provision for people with dementia. Finally, the book reflects on key findings, challenges and the way forward for long-term care for older people. The introduction, 'The concept, rationale, and implications of reablement', is available Open Access via Bristol University Press Digital.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHome care services. 0aOlder peoplexLong-term care. 0aRehabilitation. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Services & Welfare.2bisacsh1 aAspinal, Fiona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurton, Elissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClotworthy, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoh, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFeiring, Marte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFørland, Oddvar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraff, Lea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuidetti, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewin, Gill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMetzelthin, Silke, econtributor.4ctb4ht